		<![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">In 2000, when asked if e-mail helps them communicate with people they would not otherwise be able to connect with, <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[1]</FONT> of e-mail users agreed and another <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[2]</FONT> agreed strongly. Only <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[3]</FONT> responded that they disagreed and <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[4]</FONT> that they disagreed strongly. Just under <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[5]</FONT> were not sure either way. By 2001 opinions had changed dramatically. The percentage of those who <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[6]</FONT> halved, while the proportion who <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[7]</FONT> fell by just over a quarter. Correspondingly, the percentage of those who agreed or <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[8]</FONT> rose. The <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[9]</FONT> rose slightly by only 3 per cent, but the <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[10]</FONT> rose by just under <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[11]</FONT>. The fact that the percentage of those who neither agreed nor disagreed had <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[12]</FONT> by 2001 suggests that people had begun to realise the potential of the medium.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
